      "SummaryText": " the HF process operations, occurs. All employees are regularly trained and drilled on the notification and evacuation procedures detailed in the ER Plan.  GAM maintains an onsite Emergency Response Team that responds to major chemical incidents.  The team is trained to administer first aid treatment following medically-approved HF protocols.  A member of the ERT would travel with an injured person to the hospital to ensure that the appropriate treatment is continued for HF acid exposure.\n\n\n\nThe facility's emergency response plan establishes a written procedure to follow during a chemical release.  In the event of a major release, the plan calls for a facility evacuation and notification to the National Response Center, Berks County HazMat Team, local fire department, and PA DEP. \n\n\n\nThe emergency response plan also contains procedures to alert facility personnel of the danger potential; a list of emergency contacts; evacuation procedures and primary/secondary gathering locations; and the procedures to be implemented in the event of a fire at the facility. \n\n\n\nDuring the past five years, GAM has not experienced an accidental release that meets the criteria under the Risk Management Program regulations for inclusion on the five-year accident history.\n\n\n\nIn summary, GAM is fully committed to the safe storage, use, and operation of the Aqueous HF systems utilized at the facility.  GAM is committed to continuously improving the overall safety, health and environmental performance record at the Boyertown facility.  Improvements are generally achieved through policies aimed at best management practices; site- and job-specific training; process and job hazard analyses; continued coordination with local emergency response agencies; and upholding the facility's goal to be an industry leader in workplace safety as well as a good steward of the environment."
